I mean, I think two
of the books I think

00:48:32.420 --> 00:48:36.620
are books I'm just about to
send to Warren and Charlie,

00:48:36.620 --> 00:48:40.740
so I think you guys
might enjoy it.

00:48:40.740 --> 00:48:46.640
One of them is called
"The Beak of the Finch."

00:48:46.640 --> 00:48:48.800
I think Jonathan Weiner
is the name of the author.

00:48:48.800 --> 00:48:50.030
It's a very old book.

00:48:50.030 --> 00:48:53.484
I think it came
out 24 years ago.

00:48:53.484 --> 00:48:54.900
I don't know if
guys have read it.

00:48:54.900 --> 00:48:55.660
SAURABH MADAAN:
Charles Darwin related.

00:48:55.660 --> 00:48:56.534
MOHNISH PABRAI: Yeah.

00:48:56.534 --> 00:48:59.150
So I was fascinated by the book.

00:48:59.150 --> 00:49:01.910
I think that it's
talking about a couple

00:49:01.910 --> 00:49:05.930
of researchers that spent
several months a year on one

00:49:05.930 --> 00:49:09.200
of the very small
islands in the Galapagos

00:49:09.200 --> 00:49:12.260
and they did this for
more than 20 years.

00:49:12.260 --> 00:49:16.980
And to their surprise, they
saw evolution in real time

00:49:16.980 --> 00:49:18.480
with something
Darwin didn't see.

00:49:18.480 --> 00:49:20.270
So I think it's a great book--

00:49:20.270 --> 00:49:24.070
unrelated to investing, but
I think it's a great read.

00:49:24.070 --> 00:49:30.050
And then the second one
is a book called "Am I

00:49:30.050 --> 00:49:35.210
Being Too Subtle," and
that's a book by Sam Zell.

00:49:35.210 --> 00:49:37.440
And some of you might
have heard of Sam Zell.

00:49:37.440 --> 00:49:40.790
And this book, I think
what I would recommend

00:49:40.790 --> 00:49:45.000
is to listen to it,
rather than read it.

00:49:45.000 --> 00:49:49.075
So it's a good way to kill time
on the Bay Area expressways.

00:49:49.075 --> 00:49:50.950
SAURABH MADAAN: It's in
his own voice, right?

00:49:50.950 --> 00:49:51.825
MOHNISH PABRAI: Yeah.

00:49:51.825 --> 00:49:54.110
It's in his own voice.

00:49:54.110 --> 00:49:56.910
It's in his kind of
raspy Sam Zell voice.

00:49:56.910 --> 00:50:00.230
And so I've been
listening to it in my car.

00:50:00.230 --> 00:50:02.510
And I think there
are a lot of lessons,

00:50:02.510 --> 00:50:08.810
a lot of lessons for investing
and operations and culture

00:50:08.810 --> 00:50:09.320
and so on.

00:50:09.320 --> 00:50:16.010
And Sam is very candid, in
your face about the sharing.

00:50:16.010 --> 00:50:21.060
And so I think that's
another good book.

00:50:21.060 --> 00:50:25.970
And the third one,
which I'm rereading

00:50:25.970 --> 00:50:32.420
and I'm learning a lot
from, is the other biography

00:50:32.420 --> 00:50:34.532
on Charlie Munger, "Damn Right."

00:50:34.532 --> 00:50:35.990
So I know you said,
don't go there,

00:50:35.990 --> 00:50:39.980
but "Dan Right" came out
probably 17 years ago.

00:50:39.980 --> 00:50:44.240
And there's a lot of
good stuff in there

00:50:44.240 --> 00:50:48.860
in terms of some of the
different things, especially

00:50:48.860 --> 00:50:54.500
some of the evolution Warren
and Charlie went through

00:50:54.500 --> 00:50:58.820
from buying cheap assets to
focusing on better businesses.

00:50:58.820 --> 00:51:01.334
And so I think there's
a lot of lessons there.

00:51:01.334 --> 00:51:02.750
And also, there's
a lot of lessons

00:51:02.750 --> 00:51:07.040
about in many ways I
think Charlie Munger got

00:51:07.040 --> 00:51:14.780
dealt a bad hand, if you will,
a far worse hand than most of us

00:51:14.780 --> 00:51:18.440
are dealt. He had to
deal with the death

00:51:18.440 --> 00:51:23.300
of his nine-year-old son, he
had to deal with blindness

00:51:23.300 --> 00:51:27.650
in one eye after a
cataract operation that

00:51:27.650 --> 00:51:31.790
went south, and then
just the extreme pain

00:51:31.790 --> 00:51:33.810
of eviscerating that eye.

00:51:33.810 --> 00:51:38.870
And so there's a lot
of human qualities

00:51:38.870 --> 00:51:42.260
you can see in that
book where he's really

00:51:42.260 --> 00:51:44.000
been really stoic
about that in the sense

00:51:44.000 --> 00:51:50.820
that when there's been kind
of pain and suffering, in fact

00:51:50.820 --> 00:51:54.380
he's absolutely
rational about his eye.

00:51:54.380 --> 00:51:57.950
He said at the time for the
procedure he was going through,

00:51:57.950 --> 00:52:00.230
there was a 5% chance
of complications.

00:52:00.230 --> 00:52:05.590
And so his rational side
said, one out of 20 I'm

00:52:05.590 --> 00:52:08.620
going to get it and if
it happens to be me,

00:52:08.620 --> 00:52:10.414
that's the way it is.

