01:00:15.040 --> 01:00:18.730
those books to look for stocks.

01:00:18.730 --> 01:00:21.340
I mean, these days it's so
easy to find information.

01:00:21.340 --> 01:00:23.830
You can just go to GuruFocus,
use the stock screener,

01:00:23.830 --> 01:00:24.790
find P/E one.

01:00:24.790 --> 01:00:27.580
You can do that
in half a second.

01:00:27.580 --> 01:00:28.854
Why does that still work?

01:00:28.854 --> 01:00:29.770
MOHNISH PABRAI: Right.

01:00:29.770 --> 01:00:31.750
So actually, that's
a great question.

01:00:31.750 --> 01:00:39.250
Because in 2006 when he invested
in Daehan Flour in Korea

01:00:39.250 --> 01:00:43.630
you could have had
Capital IQ, you

01:00:43.630 --> 01:00:45.740
can run any screen
you wanted, it

01:00:45.740 --> 01:00:47.980
would have popped up
all kinds of companies.

01:00:47.980 --> 01:00:53.350
And if you believe that
there are tens of thousands

01:00:53.350 --> 01:00:55.830
of people with lots of
assets who have Capital IQ

01:00:55.830 --> 01:01:00.400
subscriptions, that stock should
have not been at that price.

01:01:00.400 --> 01:01:04.870
But just like the $1 bill on the
ground where the professor says

01:01:04.870 --> 01:01:07.690
it can't be a real dollar bill
because in an efficient market,

01:01:07.690 --> 01:01:09.970
there wouldn't be a
$1 bill on the ground,

01:01:09.970 --> 01:01:17.560
the reality is that the speed
of access to information

01:01:17.560 --> 01:01:23.680
is not the determining factor
in leading to market efficiency.

01:01:23.680 --> 01:01:27.430
I think that markets, because
they are auction-driven

01:01:27.430 --> 01:01:30.280
and because there are humans
involved, they vacillate

01:01:30.280 --> 01:01:31.990
between fear and greed.

01:01:31.990 --> 01:01:34.480
And at that time in
the Korean market

01:01:34.480 --> 01:01:38.140
for whatever was going on then,
there was more fear than greed.

01:01:38.140 --> 01:01:46.210
And so I find, for
example, even today there

01:01:46.210 --> 01:01:51.550
are lots of bargains in South
Korea, amazing bargains.

01:01:51.550 --> 01:01:53.710
SAURABH MADAAN: Can
you give an example?

01:01:53.710 --> 01:01:55.085
MOHNISH PABRAI:
Well, you know we

01:01:55.085 --> 01:02:00.760
are buying right now so
we can't quite go there

01:02:00.760 --> 01:02:02.030
because these things trade--

01:02:02.030 --> 01:02:05.530
I mean, some of
these things, I'm

01:02:05.530 --> 01:02:10.210
barely able to get $2,000
a day off the stock.

01:02:10.210 --> 01:02:11.830
We have a $500
million, $600 million

01:02:11.830 --> 01:02:13.930
dollar portfolio
so we are nibbling.

01:02:13.930 --> 01:02:19.210
But we're buying things at
two and a half times earnings.

01:02:19.210 --> 01:02:21.880
And I'm buying two and a half
times earnings of a business.

01:02:21.880 --> 01:02:26.120
So for example, I'll send you
on a treasure hunt, how's that?

01:02:26.120 --> 01:02:30.051
A treasure hunt is more exciting
than giving you the treasure,

01:02:30.051 --> 01:02:30.550
right?

01:02:30.550 --> 01:02:30.940
SAURABH MADAAN: Sure, sure.

01:02:30.940 --> 01:02:31.630
MOHNISH PABRAI:
It's always better

01:02:31.630 --> 01:02:32.950
to hunt for the treasure.

01:02:32.950 --> 01:02:36.880
So I mean, I have
an insight and I

01:02:36.880 --> 01:02:39.370
don't know whether the insight
will be right or wrong,

01:02:39.370 --> 01:02:40.210
you can tell me.

01:02:40.210 --> 01:02:47.640
So we know that there is lots
of different permutations

01:02:47.640 --> 01:02:51.870
and combinations of changes
happening in the way humans

01:02:51.870 --> 01:02:52.900
travel.

01:02:52.900 --> 01:02:53.400
Right?

01:02:53.400 --> 01:02:56.580
So we used to have cars
and public transport

01:02:56.580 --> 01:02:58.410
and taxis, that was it, right?

01:02:58.410 --> 01:03:03.140
Now you have Uber, you have Uber
Pool, you might get autonomous,

01:03:03.140 --> 01:03:05.550
Weymo.

01:03:05.550 --> 01:03:07.717
There's a lot of
different combinations.

01:03:07.717 --> 01:03:09.300
Some of you might
be familiar with Via

01:03:09.300 --> 01:03:12.440
in New York, which
I think is great.

01:03:12.440 --> 01:03:20.460
And so the end result is that
humans have a lot more options

01:03:20.460 --> 01:03:24.150
available for
transport and mobility

01:03:24.150 --> 01:03:26.220
and the price is coming down.

01:03:26.220 --> 01:03:28.950
And also you have low
gas prices and so on.

01:03:28.950 --> 01:03:33.240
So it is an absolute
certainty in my mind

01:03:33.240 --> 01:03:37.530
that per capita
miles being driven

01:03:37.530 --> 01:03:42.330
in some kind of public transport
for humans is going up.

01:03:42.330 --> 01:03:45.810
I mean, I remember when I was
a student, I had my bicycle

01:03:45.810 --> 01:03:48.090
and mobility was very
restricted because I was poor

01:03:48.090 --> 01:03:50.020
and I didn't have a lot
of places I could go.

01:03:50.020 --> 01:03:53.320
Now I just see with my
kids, you can go anywhere.

01:03:53.320 --> 01:03:58.500
So if miles driven per
human are going up,

01:03:58.500 --> 01:04:00.100
how can you play that?

01:04:00.100 --> 01:04:03.540
Well, one way you can play
that is tire companies.

01:04:03.540 --> 01:04:04.210
OK?

01:04:04.210 --> 01:04:08.580
So no matter what
happens, I'm almost

01:04:08.580 --> 01:04:11.160
sure there will
be more tire sold

01:04:11.160 --> 01:04:14.580
five years from now or 10 years
from now versus yesterday.

01:04:14.580 --> 01:04:20.610
And actually, if we get to
electric cars taking off,

01:04:20.610 --> 01:04:23.430
they want weight
reductions so then they

01:04:23.430 --> 01:04:24.920
make those tires paper thin.

01:04:24.920 --> 01:04:27.870
How many people
have a Tesla here?

01:04:27.870 --> 01:04:29.040
Not Tesla owners.

01:04:29.040 --> 01:04:29.657
A value crowd.

01:04:29.657 --> 01:04:30.990
SAURABH MADAAN: Value investing.

01:04:30.990 --> 01:04:32.989
MOHNISH PABRAI: They're
a hard core value crowd.

01:04:32.989 --> 01:04:33.600
All right.

01:04:33.600 --> 01:04:38.250
So you know that like the
Teslas and of the Leafs and all

01:04:38.250 --> 01:04:40.650
that, they have these
special tires which

01:04:40.650 --> 01:04:43.740
don't last very long but
cost a lot because they

01:04:43.740 --> 01:04:45.087
want to keep the weight down.

01:04:45.087 --> 01:04:47.170
And so those are even
better for the tire company,

01:04:47.170 --> 01:04:48.990
they keep wearing out very fast.

01:04:48.990 --> 01:04:54.330
So my take was that
tires will do well.

01:04:54.330 --> 01:04:58.600
And so I made an investment
in a company in India,

01:04:58.600 --> 01:05:01.170
which was really
cheap, which made

01:05:01.170 --> 01:05:05.190
one of the ingredients
that goes into rubber

01:05:05.190 --> 01:05:06.210
that goes into tires.

01:05:06.210 --> 01:05:09.060
And I think that
will do very well.

01:05:09.060 --> 01:05:13.080
And the other was
a company in Korea

01:05:13.080 --> 01:05:17.430
which is in one shape or
another in the tire business

01:05:17.430 --> 01:05:18.900
and it's growing, actually.

01:05:18.900 --> 01:05:22.080
It's going to grow quite a bit.

01:05:22.080 --> 01:05:24.350
Even without these
demographic things happening,

01:05:24.350 --> 01:05:25.590
it will still grow.

01:05:25.590 --> 01:05:30.510
And if I'm buying a two and a
half or three times, in three

01:05:30.510 --> 01:05:33.550
years I have all my cash back.

01:05:33.550 --> 01:05:35.584
So that's the beauty
of P/E of three.

01:05:35.584 --> 01:05:37.500
SAURABH MADAAN: So it's
a tire-related company

01:05:37.500 --> 01:05:41.685
in Korea with a P/E of
three for the treasure hunt.

01:05:41.685 --> 01:05:42.560
MOHNISH PABRAI: Yeah.

01:05:42.560 --> 01:05:43.210
Have fun.

01:05:48.072 --> 01:05:49.530
AUDIENCE: So I
wanted to understand

01:05:49.530 --> 01:05:52.710
how do you decide when
these three P stocks--

01:05:52.710 --> 01:05:55.835
or not even three P, stocks
like Amazon and Google,

01:05:55.835 --> 01:05:57.210
when they are
valued so much, how

01:05:57.210 --> 01:05:59.220
do you decide when
to sell stocks

01:05:59.220 --> 01:06:00.860
that have worked for you?

01:06:00.860 --> 01:06:03.207
And a quick follow-up,
do you short?

01:06:03.207 --> 01:06:04.290
MOHNISH PABRAI: I'm sorry.

01:06:04.290 --> 01:06:05.748
AUDIENCE: Do you
also short stocks?

01:06:05.748 --> 01:06:06.815
Do you short sell?

01:06:06.815 --> 01:06:07.690
MOHNISH PABRAI: Yeah.

01:06:07.690 --> 01:06:12.240
So I have never shorted
a stock in my life.

01:06:12.240 --> 01:06:15.900
I will go to my grave without
ever having shorted a stock.

01:06:15.900 --> 01:06:19.890
I would suggest you follow
that same mental model.

01:06:19.890 --> 01:06:21.510
If the only thing
you learn here is

01:06:21.510 --> 01:06:24.100
to give up shorting
if you are shorter,

01:06:24.100 --> 01:06:27.840
then I think it would
be an hour well-spent.

01:06:27.840 --> 01:06:30.710
So it's a great question.

01:06:30.710 --> 01:06:38.080
So each of us, I think,
has a limited quota

01:06:38.080 --> 01:06:45.110
of 100 baggers that will
show up in our portfolio.

01:06:45.110 --> 01:06:50.200
I think I have had more than
my quarter of 100 baggers

01:06:50.200 --> 01:06:56.730
that I was smart enough to
buy but too dumb to hold.

01:06:56.730 --> 01:06:58.140
And there's a long list.

01:06:58.140 --> 01:07:01.670
I used to own [INAUDIBLE]
Bank in '94, I don't know,

01:07:01.670 --> 01:07:05.670
it was 150 times, I probably
got like 30% return after five

01:07:05.670 --> 01:07:11.070
years; so that Blue Dot--

01:07:11.070 --> 01:07:14.330
there's this 200
baggers I did capture.

01:07:14.330 --> 01:07:20.550
I owned Amazon in 2002,
I think, at $10 a share.

01:07:20.550 --> 01:07:22.650
I think it was 10%
of my portfolio then.

01:07:22.650 --> 01:07:27.570
And I got 40% in a few months
and I was out so that's great.

01:07:27.570 --> 01:07:31.770
But anyway, so
what I have learned

01:07:31.770 --> 01:07:43.070
is don't sell the compounders
when they get fully priced

01:07:43.070 --> 01:07:48.890
and don't sell the compounders
when they get overpriced.

01:07:48.890 --> 01:07:54.770
Only sell the compounders when
it's absolutely obvious to you

01:07:54.770 --> 01:07:57.020
that it's egregiously priced.

01:07:57.020 --> 01:08:02.900
The big money is in
riding the compounders.

01:08:02.900 --> 01:08:07.280
But you have to try to get in on
them at a reasonable valuation

01:08:07.280 --> 01:08:12.290
and you have to be right on the
fact that they are compounders.

01:08:12.290 --> 01:08:15.060
And so it's a
forgiving business.

01:08:15.060 --> 01:08:17.342
You can be wrong quite a
few times and still be OK.

01:08:17.342 --> 01:08:19.550
SAURABH MADAAN: So Mohnish,
does that buy [INAUDIBLE]

01:08:19.550 --> 01:08:25.903
mean that your buy versus hold
criteria may not be identical?

01:08:25.903 --> 01:08:28.069
MOHNISH PABRAI: It is not
identical, that's correct.

01:08:28.069 --> 01:08:31.040
I mean, this is a
very difficult lesson

01:08:31.040 --> 01:08:34.250
for a cheapskate like me, it
was a very difficult lesson

01:08:34.250 --> 01:08:35.750
for Warren and Charlie.

01:08:35.750 --> 01:08:39.170
I think they learned that
lesson from See's Candy.

01:08:39.170 --> 01:08:41.640
That was a seminal
purchase for them.

01:08:41.640 --> 01:08:44.240
And the end date
they saw in that case

01:08:44.240 --> 01:08:46.160
because of the
controlled business,

01:08:46.160 --> 01:08:49.760
they could just see
the way it mushroomed.

01:08:49.760 --> 01:08:57.200
And so I think that if you get
businesses where management is

01:08:57.200 --> 01:09:01.130
exceptional or the
[INAUDIBLE] are exceptional,

01:09:01.130 --> 01:09:04.760
or in the case of
Google you get both--

01:09:04.760 --> 01:09:07.729
buy one, get one
free, which is great--

01:09:07.729 --> 01:09:11.060
then I think those
are businesses

01:09:11.060 --> 01:09:13.729
you just don't want to touch.

01:09:13.729 --> 01:09:18.649
I met some folks in India in
some of these meetings that

01:09:18.649 --> 01:09:20.359
blew me away.

01:09:20.359 --> 01:09:25.939
I mean, in some cases, I
just looked at it and said,

01:09:25.939 --> 01:09:29.170
there's tailwinds, but
in addition to tailwinds,

01:09:29.170 --> 01:09:34.430
there is a phenomenal
operator and the price

01:09:34.430 --> 01:09:36.270
below liquidation level.

01:09:36.270 --> 01:09:39.770
And so those are
all good tenants.

01:09:39.770 --> 01:09:41.899
So that's what you
want to look for.

01:09:41.899 --> 01:09:45.590
But clearly, in my opinion,
I don't buy the notion

01:09:45.590 --> 01:09:48.350
that you buy your
portfolio every day.

01:09:48.350 --> 01:09:51.470
To me, buy and
hold are different

01:09:51.470 --> 01:09:56.330
and the cheapskate in me
still wants to not pay up.

01:09:56.330 --> 01:09:58.190
But I was able to
at a point in time

01:09:58.190 --> 01:10:01.640
get to where Google was just
at the edge of making it

01:10:01.640 --> 01:10:03.770
so it made it, which is great.

01:10:03.770 --> 01:10:06.380
And that's the key
is that you want

01:10:06.380 --> 01:10:10.730
to ride the compounders
for long periods.

01:10:10.730 --> 01:10:14.197
SAURABH MADAAN: Is this
operator by any chance Piramal?

01:10:14.197 --> 01:10:15.030
Because I know you--

01:10:15.030 --> 01:10:16.363
MOHNISH PABRAI: There are many--

01:10:16.363 --> 01:10:17.660
Piramal is a great operator.

01:10:17.660 --> 01:10:20.450
That wasn't the one Piramal.

01:10:20.450 --> 01:10:22.700
But a great operator.

01:10:22.700 --> 01:10:25.670
And But no, there
are many in India,

01:10:25.670 --> 01:10:33.080
I think, who are young and
great ethos, great drive.

01:10:33.080 --> 01:10:35.390
Piramal is an example
of a compounder.

01:10:35.390 --> 01:10:40.160
And I think that if you
own something like Piramal,

01:10:40.160 --> 01:10:42.080
I would just ignore the
price for a long time,

01:10:42.080 --> 01:10:44.859
as long as Ajay is healthy.

01:10:44.859 --> 01:10:47.025
AUDIENCE: On a related
question, you first mentioned

01:10:47.025 --> 01:10:48.590
the best ideas
portfolio, thinking

01:10:48.590 --> 01:10:52.400
how it would work in terms of
management positions, impact,

01:10:52.400 --> 01:10:52.990
sizing.

01:10:52.990 --> 01:10:56.780
I was curious how
you think about that

01:10:56.780 --> 01:11:00.300
sizing relative to
margin of safety

01:11:00.300 --> 01:11:02.145
in your valuation
of the company.

01:11:02.145 --> 01:11:03.020
MOHNISH PABRAI: Yeah.

01:11:03.020 --> 01:11:05.490
So that's a good question.

01:11:05.490 --> 01:11:10.670
I think bet sizing just
gets down to conviction.

01:11:10.670 --> 01:11:13.010
Part of it gets
down to whether it's

01:11:13.010 --> 01:11:16.040
other people's
money or your money

01:11:16.040 --> 01:11:19.820
and also kind of
where you are in life.

01:11:19.820 --> 01:11:23.390
I think if you're a
young engineer at Google,

01:11:23.390 --> 01:11:27.860
you have many decades
of productive earnings

01:11:27.860 --> 01:11:29.240
ahead of you.

01:11:29.240 --> 01:11:34.910
And so the key there is
to spend less than you

01:11:34.910 --> 01:11:41.100
or earn and put it away
into places that make sense.

01:11:41.100 --> 01:11:44.180
So I would say it's probably
the mistake to have,

01:11:44.180 --> 01:11:48.330
in that situation, more
than 10 or 12 positions.

01:11:48.330 --> 01:11:51.080
And I think there's nothing
wrong with having money

01:11:51.080 --> 01:11:54.047
in an index fund or
a few index funds.

01:11:54.047 --> 01:11:55.380
I think that's a good way to go.

01:11:55.380 --> 01:11:58.040
And so if you didn't
have a lot of ideas,

01:11:58.040 --> 01:12:02.360
then you're going
to sock money away,

01:12:02.360 --> 01:12:05.600
especially in a 401(k)
with matching and so on,

01:12:05.600 --> 01:12:06.440
you could do that.

01:12:06.440 --> 01:12:09.620
And then occasionally
when things show up

01:12:09.620 --> 01:12:12.890
on the radar which
are no-brainers,

01:12:12.890 --> 01:12:15.530
then you can switch some
of the index fund money

01:12:15.530 --> 01:12:21.260
into an actual stock idea and
such and take it from there.

01:12:21.260 --> 01:12:23.630
That's how I would do it.

